[4] Review (INVS)
Date: Tue 17 Apr 2012
Source: Institut de Veille Sanitaire (InVS) [in French, machine trans. edited]
http://www.invs.sante.fr/Dossiers-thematiques/Maladies-infectieuses/Maladies-a-prevention-vaccinale/Rougeole/Points-d-actualites/Epidemie-de-rougeole-en-France.-Actualisation-des-donnees-de-surveillance-au-16-avril-2012


Since 1 Jan 2008, over 22 000 cases of measles were reported in France, with a 3rd large-scale epidemic wave compared to the 2 previous waves, and a peak in March 2011.

For 2011, 14 966 cases were reported, of which 16 showed a neurological complication, 714 severe pneumonia, and 6 died. The sharp decrease in the number of cases reported between May and October 2011 signaled the end of this 2rd wave. Since autumn 2011, there was a slight rise in the number of reported cases, approximately the same magnitude as that observed in late 2008-early 2009. However, there has been no increase in the number of cases in March 2012, as was observed in 2010 and especially 2011. Between 1 Jan and 31 Mar 2012, 356 cases were reported (including 17 severe pneumonia cases), with the number of monthly-or-fewer cases stable since December 2011. Although these data do not forecast a significant next epidemic, the updating of the immunization status of susceptible individuals with 2 doses of vaccine, particularly in the population aged 15-30 years, remains critical.

The text is supplemented by graphical illustration of the data as follows:
1. Number of measles cases per month - Mandatory notification, France, January 2008 - March 2012
2. Number of measles cases diagnosed in emergency wards per week (1 Jan 2009 to 8 Apr 2012)
3. Geographical distribution of notified measles cases from 1 Mar 2011 to 31 Mar 2012
4. Incidence of measles cases by age groups, France, from 1 Mar 2011 to 31 Mar 2012 (Source: DO, InVS)

