[7] Cameroon (North)
Date: Sun 15 Apr 2012
Source: Cameroon Tribune [in French, trans. Mod.BM, edited]
http://www.cameroon-tribune.cm/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=67860:lepidemie-de-la-rougeole-refait-surface-a-lextreme-nord&catid=7:regions&Itemid=3#contenu


Seven deaths per 2257 cases have been reported [in Cameroon] since early this year [2012] in the Far North. This revelation was made by Babila Akaou, general secretary of the governor's office of the Far North.

In 2011, the region registered 1627 cases of measles with 17 deaths. For this year [2012], the counter is already up to 2257, and the number of deaths is 7. This epidemic already involves 7 of the 28 health districts in the region.

This information was given on 11 Apr 2012 at the launch in Maroua of the 1st week's issue of shares of health, child and maternal nutrition (SASNIM). This campaign is ongoing until 15 Apr [2012] and addresses many diseases.

Through next Sunday [22 Apr 2012], doses of vaccine against polio will be administered to children aged 5 years and under, and those aged 9 months to 5 years will be vaccinated against measles. Vitamin A capsules will be administered to children 6 months to 5 years, while children from 1-5 years will be dewormed. Women who have just given birth will receive vitamin A drops. All this is free.

The authorities in charge of health have adopted 2 immunization systems: 1st to vaccinate in all health facilities; 2nd to vaccinate in public places such as markets, places of worship, and schools.

Dr. Rebecca Djao, the regional delegate of Public Health of the Far North, has seized this opportunity to educate parents about the dangers of diseases against which children must be vaccinated, namely polio and measles. She also drew attention to the importance of vitamin A and deworming of children. Judging from the jostling of parents, who after following these tips came to vaccinate their children, we can say that the message did not fall on deaf ears.

[Byline: Patrice Mbossa]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-FRA <promed-fra@promedmail.org>

[Hopefully, these 2 immunization strategies can cover many children quickly, because with 25 percent of districts involved in the epidemic, there is a high risk of it spreading to other districts of the region.

Parents must be educated about the importance of carrying their children to health centers as soon as possible. Traditional healers and religious leaders should also be involved in the fight against the epidemic.

The interactive HealthMap ProMED-mail map of Cameroon is available at: http://healthmap.org/r/01Jc. - Mods.BM/SC]

