[8] India (Orissa)
Date: Sun 29 Apr 2012
Source: Times of India [edited]
http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bhubaneswar/Measles-outbreak-feared-in-Rayagada-9-children-killed/articleshow/12917924.cms


At least 9 children have died in the past 15 days in Rayagada district's Kasipur block, which is feared to be afflicted by an outbreak of measles. The state health department collected blood samples of a few affected children on Saturday [28 Apr 2012] for a laboratory test. Kasipur, which often makes the news for poverty, malnutrition, diarrhoea, and cholera related deaths, has been witnessing a flurry of medical activities recently after the outbreak of measles at Salapash, Katraguda, and Railighati villages under Kudipari panchayat.

"Blood samples have been collected from at least 7 children, and those will be sent to the regional medical research centre in Bhubaneswar for tests to confirm whether the children are affected by measles," said the medical officer of Kasipur hospital, Saroj Kumar Naik, who went to the affected villages along with deputy director of health K K Rout and Rayagada CDMO K V S Chowdhury.

Villagers claim that while as many as 9 children aged between 6 months to 3 years have already succumbed to measles, scores more are affected at the 3 villages, which lie at a distance of about 80 km from the district headquarters town of Rayagada. Locals alleged that due to the inaccessibility of the villages, health officials never come to their villages and healthcare facilities are virtually non-existent in the areas.

"The children succumbed to the disease at the villages without medical attention. In the absence of proper medical facilities, people depend on traditional methods of treatment and are succumbing to diseases," said Narendra Jhodia of Salapash, which lies on the border of Rayagada and Kalahandi districts.

However, officials said only 3 and not 9 children have died of measles. "There have been 9 deaths in 3 villagers in the past 2 weeks but not all from measles. Till now, we suspect 3 deaths to be from measles. Around 12 children are suffering from fever, and a medical team is campaigning at the village," said Naik. "Presently, our 1st priority is to contain the disease. Creating awareness against the disease has been initiated, and re-immunization programmes have been launched at the periphery villages to ensure that the disease does not spread to other areas," he added.

According to the medical officer, while the inaccessibility of the villages is creating an obstacle for the health workers in regularly visiting the areas, people's faith on traditional methods of treatment is also causing problems in arresting the situation. "People agree to follow our advice to combat the disease but never follow it. They organize pujas and depend on sorcery to cure the disease instead of taking medicines. It is a common practice among the tribal community to conduct pujas for 7 days to cure a disease, and if they fail in their attempt, only then will they take the patient to a hospital, by which time it is often too late," the medical officer said.

--
Communicated by:
Kunihiko Iizuka

[Measles vaccine coverage (by a monovalent vaccine at 9 months of age) in India has been good, but measles incidence remains high in parts of India. Measles, even in previously healthy children, can be a serious illness requiring hospitalization. As many as one in 20 children with measles develops pneumonia, and about one child in every 1000 who get measles will develop encephalitis, which may leave a child deaf or even mentally retarded. In developing countries, where malnutrition and vitamin A deficiency are common, mortality from measles virus infection can be considerable. Sub-acute sclerosing pan-encephalitis (SSPE), a fatal degenerative disease of the central nervous system, can be a very rare consequence of measles infection early in life.

Rayagada is a municipality in Rayagada district in the Indian state of Orissa. It is the administrative headquarters of Rayagada district. A map of Koraput, Orissa, can be accessed at: http://www.mapsofindia.com/maps/orissa/districts/koraput.htm. A ProMED-mail HealthMap can be found at http://healthmap.org/r/2i2v. - Mod.CP]

